<section xml:id="sec_second-examplesB" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Examples B</title>
  
  <paragraphs>
    <title>DC Circuits</title>
    
<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A 12 V battery with an internal resistance of 1 ohm is connected to four other resistors 
      as shown in figure below.  Find 
      <image source="fig31a.png" width="35%"> </image>
      <ol marker="a.">
        <li>
          the voltage across and the current through each resistor.
        </li>
        <li>
          the voltage <m>V_{ab}</m> across the battery, and
        </li>
        <li>
          the the electrical potential at point c.
        </li>
      </ol>
      Provided: <m>R_{1} =1 \,\Omega; \quad R_{2}= 2\,\Omega;</m> 
      <m> R_{3}= 3\,\Omega; \quad R_{4}= 6\,\Omega; </m> and <m>E = 12\,V</m>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      (<em>Find equivalent resistance and work backward to get voltage and current.</em>)
    </p>
    <p>
      Given: <m> r= 1\,\Omega;\quad R_{1} =1 \,\Omega; \quad R_{2}= 2\Omega;</m>	
      <m>R_{3}= 6\,\Omega;\quad R_{4}= 3\,\Omega;\quad E = 12\,V</m>	
    </p>
   
    <p>  
      Since <m>R_{1}</m> and <m>R_{2}</m> are in series, we have 
      <image source="fig31a.png" width="35%"> </image>
      <me>
        R_{12} = R_{1}+R_{2} = 3 \,\Omega;
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      Since <m>R_{12}</m> and <m>R_{3}</m> are in parallel, we have
       <image source="fig31b.png" width="35%"> </image> 
      <me>
        \frac{1}{R_{123}}= \frac{1}{R_{12}} + \frac{1}{R_{3}};
      </me>
      <me>
        \therefore R_{123} = 2 \,\Omega 
      </me>
       </p>
       <p>
        Since <m>r, \quad R_{123},</m> and <m>R_{4}</m> are in series, we have 
      <image source="fig31c.png" width="35%"> </image> 
        <me>
        R_{1234}= r + R_{123} +  R_{4} = 6 \,\Omega 
      </me>
       </p>
       <p>
        Now, from  figure below, we have 
        <image source="fig31d.png" width="35%"> </image> 
        <me>
         \left[ V = I R \right];
        </me>
        <me>
         or, \quad  I = \frac{V}{R} = \frac{E}{R_{1234}} = 12/6 = 2\,A
        </me>
         </p>
      <p>
        <em>Moving backward: </em>
        from  figure <image source="fig31c.png" width="35%"> </image> 
        <me>
          V_{o} = I r =2\,A\cdot1\,\Omega = 2\,V;
        </me>
        <me>
          \text{ also,} \quad V_{4} = I R_{4}= 2\,A\cdot3\,\Omega = 6\,V 
        </me>
        <me>
          \text{and} \quad  V_{123} = I R_{123}= 2\,A\cdot2\,\Omega = 4\,V 
        </me>
         </p>
 <p>
  from  figure <image source="fig31b.png" width="35%"> </image> 
  <me>
    \because \quad  V_{12} = I_{12} R_{12}; 
  </me>
  <me>
    \therefore I_{12} =  \frac{V_{12}}{R_{12}} = \frac{V_{123}}{R_{12}} = 1.33 \,A
  </me>
  <me>
    \text{also,} \quad \because \quad  V_{3} = I_{3} R_{3};
  </me>
  <me>
    \therefore I_{3} =  \frac{V_{3}}{R_{3}} = \frac{V_{123}}{R_{3}} = 0.67 \,A
  </me>
  </p>
 <p>
  from  figure <image source="fig31a.png" width="35%"> </image> 
  <me>
    \because \quad  V_{1} = I_{1} R_{1} = I_{12} R_{1}  = 1.33\,A\cdot 1\,\Omega = 1.33 \,V
  </me>
  <me>
    \text{also,}\quad \because \quad  V_{2} = I_{12} R_{2}=1.33\,A\cdot 2\,\Omega  = 2.67\, V
  </me>
  </p>
 
    <p>
      <ol marker="a.">
        <li>
          <me>
            V_{o}=2\,V;
          </me>
          <me>
            I_{o}=2\,A;
          </me>
          <me>
            V_{1}=1.33\,V;
          </me>
          <me>
            I_{1}=1.33\,A;
          </me>
          <me>
            V_{2}=2.67\,V;
          </me>
          <me>
            I_{2}=1.33\,A; 
          </me>
          <me>
            V_{4}=6\,V;
          </me>
          <me>
            I_{4}=2\,A;
          </me>
          <me>
            V_{3}=4\,V;
          </me>
          <me>
            I_{3}=0.67\,A
          </me>         
        </li>
        <li>
          <me>
            V_{ab}=E - V_{o}= 10\,V
          </me>   
        </li>
        <li>
          <me>
            V_{c}= V_{cb}=V_{2}+V_{4} = 8.67\,V
          </me>
           </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      In figures below the emf of the battery is 6 V, the internal resistance is <m>10 \,\Omega,</m> 
      and the load resistance is <m>4 \,k\Omega.</m>  Find the readings of the ammeter and the voltmeter 
      in each of the three cases. 
    </p>
    <sidebyside widths="30% 30% 30%">
      <image source="fig32a.png"> </image> 
      <image source="fig32b.png" > </image> 
      <image source="fig32c.png" > </image> 
    </sidebyside>
     </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <ol marker="i.">
        <li>
          For first figure
          <me>
            E = 6 \,V;\quad r = 10 \,\Omega;\quad  R= 4000 \,\Omega 
          </me>
          <me>
            R_{T} = r +R;
          </me>
          <me>
            V_{T} = I R_{T};
          </me>
          <me>
            V = I R
          </me>
          <me>
            R_{T} = 4010 \,\Omega;
          </me>
          <me>
            I = 1.496 \,mA;
          </me>
          Hence, Ammeter  reads  1.496 mA.
          <me>
            V = 5.985 \,V; 
          </me>
          Hence, Voltmeter reads 5.985 V.
            </li>
            <li>
              For second figure [<xref ref="subsec-el_instrmnt"/>]
              No current flows. Hence, Ammeter reads 0 current and Voltmeter reads 6 V.
               </li>
               <li>
                For third figure
                No current flows. Hence,  Ammeter  reads 0 current and Voltmeter reads 6 V.
               </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
     <term> Note:</term> <em>Ammeter</em> is a negligibly low internal resistance device. 
     It could not appreciably affect any current that is flowing in the sircuit. 
     Hence it is always used as a series connection in the circuit.
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>Voltmeter</em> is an infinitely high internal resistance device. 
     It could not allow any current flows through it from the circuit. 
     Hence it is always used as a parallel connection in the circuit element at which we are measuring the voltage.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

</paragraphs>


<paragraphs>
  <title>Kirchhoff's Law</title>
  
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        In the figure given below find 
        <image source="fig38a.png" width="40%"> </image> 
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            the current through point a, 
          </li>
          <li>
            the current through point b, 
          </li>
          <li>
            the current through point c,
          </li>
          <li>
            the voltage at point d with respect to point c.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Use loop currents direction as <m>+ve.</m>
        <image source="fig38b.png" width="40%"> </image> 
        <me>
        \text{(in loop i_1)} \quad 1 \,\Omega \, I_{1} + 2 \,\Omega \,I_{1} + 3 \,\Omega \,I_{1} - 3 \,\Omega \,I_{2}  = 5\,V
        </me>
        <me>
          \text{(in loop i_2)} \quad  3\Omega \,I_{2} - 3 \,\Omega \,I_{1}+ 4 \,\Omega \,I_{2} + 5 \,\Omega \,I_{2} - 5 \,\Omega\,I_{3}  = 10 \,V
        </me>
        <me>
          \text{(in loop i_3)} \quad 6\Omega \,I_{3} + 5 \,\Omega \,I_{3}- 5 \,\Omega \,I_{2}  = -5 \,V
        </me>
           </p>
           <p>
            Simplified form of the above equations:
            <men xml:id="eqn-kch1">
              6 \,I_{1}   - 3\, I_{2}  + 0\cdot \,I_{3} =  5 
            </men>
            <men xml:id="eqn-kch2">
              - 3 \,I_{1} + 12 \,I_{2}   - 5 \,I_{3}  =  10
            </men>
            <men xml:id="eqn-kch3">
              0 \cdot \,I_{1}   - 5 \,I_{2} + 11 \,I_{3} = - 5 
            </men>
              </p>
              <p>
                In matrix form: 
                <me>
                  \begin{bmatrix} 
                              6 &amp; -3 &amp; 0\\
                                    -3 &amp; 12 &amp; -5\\
                                        0 &amp; -5 &amp; 11
                                      \end{bmatrix} 
                                      \begin{bmatrix}
      I_{1}\\
      I_{2}\\
      I_{3}
    \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}
            5\\
              10\\
                -5
                \end{bmatrix}
                </me>
                <me>
                  \text{or,}\quad  
                  \begin{vmatrix}
                  6 &amp; -3 &amp; 0 : 5\\
                  -3 &amp; 12 &amp; -5 : 10\\
                  0 &amp; -5 &amp; 11 : -5
                  \end{vmatrix}
                </me>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      The Determinant of the matrix:
<me>
  D =\begin{Vmatrix}
6 &amp; -3 &amp; 0\\
-3 &amp; 12 &amp; -5\\
0 &amp; -5 &amp; 11
\end{Vmatrix}  
</me>
<me>
  = 6[12\times 11 -(-5)(-5)] -(-3)[-3\times 11-0]+0= 543
</me>
<me>
  I_{1}=\frac{\begin{Vmatrix}
5 &amp; -3 &amp; 0\\
10 &amp; 12 &amp; -5\\
-5 &amp; -5 &amp; 11
\end{Vmatrix}}{D} 
</me>
<me>
  =\frac{5[12\times11-(-5)(-5)]-(-3)[10\times11 -(-5)(-5)]+0}{D} = 1.45\,A
</me>
<me>
  I_{2}=\frac{\begin{Vmatrix}
6 &amp; 5 &amp; 0\\
-3 &amp; 10 &amp; -5\\
0 &amp; -5 &amp; 11
\end{Vmatrix}}{D} 
</me>
<me>
  =\frac{6[10\times11-(-5)(-5)]-5[-3\times11 -0]+0}{D} = \frac{675}{543} = 1.24\,A
</me>
<me>
  I_{3}=\frac{\begin{Vmatrix}
6 &amp; -3 &amp; 5\\
-3 &amp;  12 &amp; 10\\
0 &amp; -5 &amp; -5
\end{Vmatrix}}{D} 
</me>
<me>
  =\frac{6[12\times(-5)-(-5)(10)]-(-3)[-3\times(-5) -0]+5[(-3)\times(-5)-0]}{D} 
</me>
<me>
  \therefore \quad I_{3}== \frac{60}{543} = 0.11\,A
</me>
         </p>
         <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <m> I_{a} = I_{1} = 1.45\,A;</m>
            </li>
            <li>
             <m>I_{b} = I_{2} = 1.24\,A;</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>I_{c} = I_{3} = 0.11\,A;</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m> V_{dc} = -[1I_{1} +2I_{1}]= -4.36\,V</m>
             <p>
              - ve sign is taken because current is going from point a to d.
             </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
              </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A galvanometer is used as the meter in a multimeter. The galvanometer has a resistance of 
        <m>10 \,\Omega</m> and reads full scale when <m>1 \,mA</m> is flowing through it. 
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            What is the minimum voltage that will cause the galvanometer to read full scale? 
          </li>
          <li>
            What shunt resistance must be used in parallel with the galvanometer to make an ammeter that reads up to 0.1 A? 
          </li>
          <li>
            What resistance must be placed in series with the galvanometer to make a voltmeter with a maximum range of 20 V? 
          </li>
          <li>
            What is the voltage when the voltmeter reads one-quarter full scale? 
          </li>
        </ol>
          </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Given:	<m> g = 10 \,\Omega;\quad	I_{g} = 1.00\times10^{-3} \,A;</m> <m>I_{b} = 0.1 \,A; \quad	V_{c} = 20 \,V</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
           <me>
            V_{a} = I_{a} \,g; \quad I_{a} = I_{g} 
           </me>
           <me>
           \therefore \quad V_{a}=10 \,mV
           </me>
              <image source="fig39a.png" width="40%"> </image> 
          </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              V_{b} =V_{a} = I_{b} R_{b}; 
            </me>
            <me>
              \quad R_{b} = 0.1\, \Omega;
            </me>
            <me>
              \frac{1}{R_{b}}=\frac{1}{g}+\frac{1}{s} 
            </me>
            <me>
              \therefore \quad  s=0.1 \,\Omega
            </me>
             <image source="fig39b.png" width="40%"> </image> 
          </li>
          <li>
           <me>
            V_{c} = V_{g} R_{c}; 
           </me>
           <me>
            R_{c} = g+s=20 \,k\Omega 
           </me>
           <me>
            \therefore \quad s = 19.99 \,k\Omega
           </me>
           <image source="fig39c.png" width="40%"> </image> 
          </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              V_{d} = \frac{1}{4}V_{c}= 5 \,V
            </me>
            </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The capacitor in the R-C circuit shown below contains no charge. The switch S is closed 
        at time t = 0. If E = 6 V, <m>C = 5 \,\mu F</m> and <m>R = 2 \,M\Omega,</m> find 
        <image source="fig41a.png" width="40%"> </image> 
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            the time constant of the circuit,
          </li>
          <li>
            the voltage across the resistor when t = 5 s,
          </li>
          <li>
            the charge on the capacitor when t = 5 s, and 
          </li>
          <li>
            the current through the battery when t = 5 s.
          </li>
        </ol>
            </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Given: <m>E=6\,V; \quad C = 5.00\times10^{-6}\,F;</m> 
        <m>R = 2.00\times10^{6}\,\Omega; \quad t =6\,s. </m>
        <me>
          E =\frac{q}{C}+IR; \quad I=\frac{\,dq}{\,dt};\quad V_{r} = IR
        </me>
        <me>
          E- \frac{q}{C} =\frac{\,dq}{\,dt}R; 
        </me>
        <me>
          or,\quad \frac{E}{R}- \frac{q}{RC} =\frac{\,dq}{\,dt}
        </me>
        
        <me>
         or,\quad \frac{EC-q}{RC} =\frac{\,dq}{\,dt};
        </me>
        <me>
          or, \quad \frac{\,dq}{EC-q} = \frac{\,dt}{RC}
        </me>
        <me>
          or, \quad  \int\limits_{0}^{Q}\frac{\,dq}{EC-q}=\int\limits_{0}^{t}\frac{\,dt}{RC}; 
        </me>
        <me>
          or, \quad  \left.\frac{\ln(EC-q)}{-1}\right]_{0}^{Q} = \frac{t}{RC}
        </me>
        <me>
          or, \quad   \ln(EC-Q)-\ln(EC) =-\frac{t}{RC};
        </me>
        <me>
          or, \quad \ln\frac{EC-Q}{EC}=-\frac{t}{RC}
        </me>
        <me>
          or, \quad   EC-Q =ECe^{-\frac{t}{RC}};
        </me>
        <me>
         or, \quad Q = EC[1-e^{\frac{-t}{RC}}]
        </me>
        
        <me>
          or, \quad   Q=Q_{o}[1-e^{\frac{-t}{\tau}}]
        </me>
     differentiate w.r.t 't', we get-
     <me>
      I =I_{o}e^{-t/\tau}
     </me>
     <me>
      \text{let}\quad I_{o}= \frac{E}{R} = 3.0\,\mu A; \quad \tau = RC;\quad EC = Q_{o} [\text{maximum charge}]
     </me>
         </p>
         <p>
          Now,
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <m> \tau = 10\,s;\quad Q_{o}= 30 \,\mu C;\quad e^{-\frac{t}{\tau}}= 0.606 </m>
            </li>
            <li>
             <m>Q=11.81 \,\mu C</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>V_{R}= 3.639 \,V</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m> I = 1.82 \,\mu A</m>
            </li>
          </ol>
         </p>
       </solution>
  </example>
</paragraphs>
